title: Tevo Tarantula / OctoPrint / Endoscope Camera Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Long time ago, Amazon was a treasure trove for those of us who provided HONEST reviews in exchange for products. Amazon put a stop to that, but back then, one of the items I scored was an endoscope camera. I used it a few of times so I could review it, but it has sat on a shelf since. Enter OctoPrint / OctoPi. Turns out, this camera works perfectly with OctoPrint - just follow the directions on - https://github.com/foosel/OctoPrint/wiki/Webcams-known-to-work.

The problem, though, was how to mount the camera. Ten minutes in Sketchup and thirty minutes print time, yielded me with a suitable mount. The camera is a snug fit at a 22.5° angle and there is a guide on the rear to prevent the mount from pivoting. The mount is secured to the rail slightly above the build plate using a 4mm screw and a t-nut.

The built-in LED lights of the endoscope are not a sufficient enough light source to adequately light the build plate, so you'll also need to install some sort of lighting fixture.

-=[ EDIT ]=-
Apparently, somehow, this model wasn't watertight. I swear I thought it was. Anyway, I have uploaded the corrected version.

comments.author: datixx

comments.text: Depending on the endoscope you are using - eBay, Amazon, generic Chinese - you will need to edit your file differently. For mine, the Amazon version, you open the file on your OctoPi system /boot/octopi.txt. Find the line that reads [#camera_usb_options="-r 640x480 -f 10"]. Ignore all [ ] brackets. Those are just to show where each line starts/stops. Under that add a new line to read [camera_usb_options="-q 75 -y"]. Then, look for this line [#additional_brokenfps_usb_devices=("046d:082b" "aabb:ccdd")]. Under that you will need to add a new line to read [additional_brokenfps_usb_devices=("f007:b999")]. The numbers [f007:b999] will be different on your system. This is the device ID number. You will have to determine that yourself by ssh'ing into the Pi. Without the USB camera plugged in on the Pi, type [dmesg]. Now plug your camera in and wait a few seconds. When you run [dmesg]  again, you should see a new entry. That will be your camera and you will need the digits shown for that entry.

title: Bicycle Dynamo Spoke Clip for Bicycle Touring

description.text:
Warning: This is an experimental tool, and you will be using both your bicycle dynamo and your wheel spokes in a way that they were never intended to be used. Do not use your bicycle for travel while these clips are attached. These spoke clips were designed with the dimensions of my own personal bicycle in mind, and may require adjustments to properly fit yours.You may damage expensive or difficult to replace parts of your bike by using these, and you may be far from home when that damage occurs -- please test carefully in advance of any trips and do not take any unnecessary risks. Use of these spoke clips is at your own risk!

These clips allow you to use your bicycle's hub dynamo as a power source even while giving your legs a break.

Brief Instructions (see video on youtube):

  1. Flip your bike upside-down.
  2. Clip one of these to every pair of spokes on the tire-side of where the spokes cross (i.e. closer to the tire rather than the hub) on the non-drive side of your bike (i.e. the side without your chain and gears). Attaching a clip to every pair is recommended to prevent your paracord from derailing and violently detaching nearby spoke clips.
  3. Run a segment of shock cord or paracord around the outside of your newly-attached spoke clips.
  4. Tie both sides of your paracord together tightly enough that the cord rests snugly inside your spoke clips, but not anywhere near tight enough to bend your spokes.
  5. Pedal with your hands. It'll help if you up-shift to your highest gear.

Every fall, I try to take a week off to do a little bike touring down a short segment of the Oregon Coast. I do it a little differently from most people, though, by not taking vacation time, and instead working in the morning, and traveling in the evening. This sort of arrangement requires a few scarce things:

  1. Determination & discipline: It's sometimes incredibly difficult to focus on being productive when you're sitting next to the beach on your laptop. Don't do this if you have difficulty working in awe-inspiringly beautiful environments.
  2. Cell coverage: This should be obvious, but I need to be tethered wherever I'm camping out. This sometimes requires some ingenuity and backup planning.
  3. Power: Hiker-biker campsites rarely have power, and finding an electrical outlet at a day use area is not guaranteed. I have a bike dynamo for running my lights and charging my phone, but the dynamo adds a little resistance, and those hills can be really tough, so they are typically rated for just 3W. That's just not enough power, so batteries are a must. Unfortunately, those usually require stopping off at a car camping site every few days for a night to recharge.

I'd like to worry less about the last option. Car camping sites are often much less idyllic than hiker-biker sites, and almost always devoid of the interesting conversations that campfire shared with other hikers and bikers provides. This experiment was intended to help with extending that range.

description.text:
Technological innovation has advanced digitization of photography systems.
Enlarger lenses which became unnecessary by digitalization are sold at auction.
Enlarger lenses are inexpensive and often have good performance.

Therefore, a photographing system with bellows was constructed.

Da an unserer Heizung, im Winter, an einem Wochenende dieses Teil ausgefallen war, hatte ich keine andere Wahl, als es im CAD nach zu konstruieren (nach dem was vom Original noch über war).

EN:
This Spinner is especially designed for the smallest of the house, when using standard bearings 624zz (13x4x5) fits in the smaller hands (not recommended for children under 4 years).

For easy printing and assembly, the pates fit with click (depending on the calibration of your printer), if you need to glue, with ABS you can use paste (ABS + Acetone) without problems. Also, if the holes are small, place the bearings aligned above the holes and warm the bearings with the tip of a welder, when they are hot they will melt the plastic around them and pushing carefully insert them.

This project had to do so because my little daughter could not play with the Spinners of her cousins for being too big for her. Now enjoy as you burn it.

description.text:
A customizable box for Wemos D1 R2 dual base board projects. The box has many ventilation grills and the lid has a vertical wall in order to minimize the thermal transfer between the warm ESP8266 board on one side and a sensor shield on the other side.

Currently designed for for female headers on the base board, and male headers on the Wemos module and shields. You can build a smaller case if you plan to solder the male headers directly on the base board (reduce the interior height). Adjust the interior margin for more space, i.e. if you want to use DHT11/22 based shields.

Typically you would like to change only ww (wall width), im (interior margin, clearance), lsh (largest wemos shield, or stack height) and fhh (female header height - set to 0 if soldering the male headers directly on the base board). description.text: Over the vacation I built a set of Arduino based sensors for my Vera home controler. It uses a nRF24L01 wireless device, and overall lowers the cost of a home built sensor to less that $10. You can read more here: http://code.mios.com/trac/mios_arduino-sensor# This sensor is used with the vera Z-wave controller to automatically turn on the bathroom fan when the humidity goes high. I created this sensor enclosure to make it presentable for wall mount. This box still needs that added, but it is still very much a prototype towards the final design. This design uses obijuan's parameterized battery back for power. It integrated well for the 6V I needed to power the 5V Arduino Pro Mini. Please note that the wireless device is 3.3 volts, So, you will need that power regulator that is called out in the mios site. This design could be used for other non-home control designs. Perhaps just a light prototype box for the Pro Mini. Have fun! Let me know what you think.

description.text: This is a hand saw guide for keeping a saw blade perpendicular to the surface of a cut as well as a jig to keep the saw along the desired cutting path. It uses recessed magnets to keep the saw blade flat against the guide but takes advantage of the low friction between the metal blade and the plastic guide, allowing for smooth "sawing" action. Print, glue in magnets, clamp to a work piece, and get those perfect cuts you've been after. The magnets that this was designed to work with can be found on Amazon here More info on my blog

I have had good results using hexagonal infill pattern. I recommend printing with at least 20% infill as the base will see some clamping pressure. Once printed, glue in magnets. This was designed for 1/2"x1/8" N48 Neodymium magnets that can be found on Amazon [here]( http://www.amazon.com/Neodymium-Magnets-inch-Disc-N48/dp/B001KV38ES) I have had great success using PVC pipe glue with PLA but any epoxy should work as well. Most super glues work with ABS.

description.text:
This is a cool robot wheel I designed during my lunch period. :) It is scalable, But if You scale it, remember to adjust the axle hole size. I usually make mine at 50% size. This might actually make a decent flywheel if made of metal.
It was supposed to be a pulley, but made a better wheel. UPDATE:
I added a wheel with five spokes instead of three. It is also smaller.

Cut out of whatever material you want. I cut mine out of 6mm Sintra (expanded PVC) and it worked really well. You can put a rubber band around the outside for better grip, or cut a groove around the outside and put in an o-ring.
I included the cb (CamBam) CAM file, and the ngc (GCode) file. Adjust as needed.

I'm sure there is something like this already, but this is to mount a spool of the type that "repraper" sells on top of the bars, only using printed parts and 4 skate bearings. It was designed for minimal use of vitamins, and uses around 1.5m of 3mm plastic to make.
Print 8 of the bearing.stl, and glue one on each side of each skate bearing. The main body of the holder just rests on grooves on the top bars, then the bearings are held in place by the spool.

comments.text:
i used this a while ago until my Spool crashed down to the floor almost taking the printer with it.
seems like one of the bearings wandered of, and so the spool "lost balance".
i suggest adding something like a hook on the ends to keep the bearings in place

I can't find the stls now, but they should be easy to design if you want. Another option is to flare out the ends of a stump with a soldering iron or other form of heat so the bearings can't slip off.

description.text:
There are many cool things on thingiverse that use soda bottle threads, but the problem is... we don't really drink soda at our house.  We do sometimes go for the Simply brand juices though (very tastey) so I decided to figure out some threads that fit those bottles.  
They also have a wider mouth so it opens up some more possibilities for like animal feeders and stuff like that.  But first things first, here are the threads it uses.

There are three variations of threads because  I swear I think makerware is filling in the shells on the inside of holes...  
So the deal is the actual measurements are the first versions of each file ("internal" is for subtracting, the "test" is an already subtracted version).  The xxx_plus_one and xxx_plus_two variants have a 1mm and 2mm dia bigger hole.   
Pictured is simply_threads_test_plus_two.stl printed with makerware at 2 shells, 10% infill.  (I did cancel it before it finished, so it should be the full height if allowed to complete.)

description.text:
The original band for my Pebble watch snapped in half on the hole side due to fatigue, and after a year or so the replacement band (which was made of a relatively stiff plastic) is about to do the same thing.

Since I recently acquired some flexible filament (Maker Geeks Maker Flex TPEE), and didn't feel like wasting ~$10 to buy another full watch band, I decided to just model and print my own version of the one that is failing. I reused the existing spring-loaded retaining pin.

The resulting part is considerably more flexible than the one it is replacing, and thus feels less likely to wear out as quickly. As my filament is Candy Apple Red rather than black, it doesn't really match the rest of the watch, but I don't care.

title: 608 bearing using BBs with source for fidget spinners
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A 608 bearing using BBs. Source is included and well documented if you want a different size. I printed in PLA. No supports needed. It's an easy print. There is a 3mm gap between the inner and outer ring. Add half the BBs and then force the remaining through the gap. PLA is flexible enough to let you push the BBs in but the BBs are completely secure once in. In order to help it spin and get the 11th BB, the outer ring and inner ring have slightly different bore sizes which gives it a little bit looser fit and allows it to spin faster.

title: My Steampunk Family - A Series of Relief Portraits
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
A series of relief portraits of my family in their steampunk gear. These were created as a Christmas/Mother's day present for my mother.

Frame file found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2309286

The portraits were first created from pictures with the lithophane generator http://3dp.rocks/lithophane/

Prior to using the generator, the 2D images are made B/W and then I modify the relative intensity of the "colors" to control how far the features in the images will pop out. The background is made to be the lightest part of the image so that the generator makes it the thinnest part.

After the lithophane is generated, I use Meshmixer to finish pulling out details. The first thing I do is get more "contrast" by increasing the scale in Z. This appears to not make everything thicker but actually increases the z-difference between the parts, literally increasing contrast. After I increase the contrast, there is a lot of manual sculpting work to finish pulling the features out where I want them and to sculpt the faces so they are less lithophane and more relief as well as better match the original picture.

comments.text: Really nice result, must have been quite some work making these bas reliefs. Tempting to try in Meshmixer.

comments.text: Thanks!  Actually the hardest part was getting the base 2D picture setup so that the 3DRocks Lithophane generator gave a model that I liked and felt only needed some minor finishing.  This required a lot of time in Gimp, making everything into B&W and then reversing color and lightening/darkening if I wanted a part to jut out more or less.  The time spent in Meshmixer was nice and relaxing as all I was doing was touch-up shaping.

We printed 2 pyramids as you can see on pictures. We used PLA form SOVB 3D french brand for the bronze one, the other one is ABS silver from E-SUN.
note: WEASY 3 is a Prusa-design-based 3d printer we propose on www.easy-3d-store.fr

The other constraint was the printing feasibility, with no support and being able to be downscaled to any printer size.

title: Rifle Rest / Cradle for Tripod - Hunting

description.text:
Now that I've used for several hunting trips, I've added a quick release (get a good one they aren't horribly expensive) allows you to leave it on the rifle or stow it quick in a bag. A ball mount or pendulum mount works nice for most applications.

v2 - Upside down 1/4-20 flange nut allows for a shorter screw engagement on the tripod. Add foam tape used 1/4 x 1" pads and reduces noise. Nicely balanced rifles sit on it very without straps.

This is designed to hold rifles to a tripod for a nice steady shot, great for long range shots when prone isn't an option. (heavy tripods work best) It uses a Std. 1/4-20 nut which fits almost all Photography tripods. (can be had cheap at most thrift shops-I don't take my good tripods hunting) Idea being it's a cradle for the gun and straps over the top secure it in place. Keep in mind this works great on mono-pods too, anything with a 1/4-20 screw will mount to it so it's kind of versatile.

If you want to try the other parts, curious about the grip click on the grip link.

I recently replaced the 5mm timing cables for the X and Y axis on my Reprap Prusa with SynchroMesh Cable.
(https://sdp-si.com/eStore/PartDetail.asp?Opener=Group&PartID=84751&GroupID=768) I used the pulleys (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15923) shared by Granz initially with a 15 tooth pulley. Looking at the pulley in situ it was very obvious to me that it is very much more compact than your average 5mm belt pulley. A plan was hatched. I had planned on producing a torsion box for my Y-Axis motor since seeing Lanthans example(http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11017). However I realised that using the much more compact synchromesh cable pulleys left plenty of stepper motor axle. So I created a torsion box that instead of holding a pulley within a bearing, grips the 5mm axle directly. As the 5mm axles are machined to very low tolerances, I can achieve very precise constraint on the stepper motor axle. The design uses the 695ZZ miniature bearing a readily available item from ebay, but as the scad file is parametric you can of course alter the bearing trap to suit what you have available. This design is a derivative of Spacexula's Y Bracket, which in turn is a derivative of Prusa's I believe. If you wish to, you can also print a reverse bearing trap which is designed to constrain the motor axle at the other end for motor designs that allow this. I also included options in the scad file to print a calibration piece so that you can fine tune your hole sizes to achieve good tolerances. I made a short recording of the mount in action... http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZdSNRCEeU64

Print the Y motor Bracket, and the bearing trap stl files. Print the pulley (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15923) and insert a 608ZZ bearing. Optionally you can also print the reverse bearing trap if you want to constrain the motor axle on both ends. Not all stepper motors have the axle protruding from both sides. Next disasemble the existing front Y-axis bracket Insert the SynchroMesh pulley on the stepper motor and position it so the centre groove is approx 10.94mm from the stepper motor mounting plate. Reassemble the torsion box in the order shown in the photographs. There are two M8 washers either side of the 608ZZ bearing. While you are doing it it will be easier if you feed the cable through the pulleys while the torsion box is still open. Bolt the torsion box to the stepper motor with M3 25mm bolts. Tighten everything up, positioning your motor mount so that the Synchro mesh cable is as parallel as possible to the Y-axis smooth rods. Marvel at the complete lack of unwanted movement in your Y-Axis motor.

This really solves the flexing problem of the original bracket, and the extra support on the 5mm shaft is a great idea.  I'm currently building a large printer with a 360mm x 400mm x 300mm build area that is constructed with extruded aluminum, and your design has inspired me to use a torsion box for the Y-axis motor on this printer.  Thanks for sharing this!

description.text:
A fidget spinner featuring the logo of reprap, the main 3d printer self-replication movement. A little bit on the larger side (diameter almost 3 inches) but should still work just fine.

Both normal versions take a 608 skate bearing for the center ring. The one spinner is unweighted, so should be printed with a high infill. The other accepts American pennies one the bottom for weights, offering a cheap and effective alternative to extra bearings (you probably have 3 cents to spare!)

No bearings at all? The other spinner type uses @emmett 's gear bearing. I'm not sure how well it'll work on such a small scale, but I'd like to see it! Again, weighted and unweighted versions available.

The spinner caps are modified versions of those posted in @2ROBOTGUY 's Tri Fidget Spinner Toy (that I initially discovered in @berky93 's Pulsar Spinner. Thanks!). One has the reprap "teardrop" logo, the other the words "rep rap." I suggest the logo one, as the details are much more obvious, but both are included. They probably won't fit in the gear bearing version, but then again, that bearing is so awesome who would want to cover it?

Support the creators of your favorite printers and Make one today!
